I'm having a hard time understanding how the language used by Project Blah members came into being. I'm assuming, for one, that all the unusual words in this article are made up by the author, and not drawn from real isolated languages. So, is this a case where Blah initiates who perceive the object are making spontaneous observations like  and others are nodding along, like these words are just coming to them naturally as descriptors for its qualities? Or is it more along the lines of these being agreed upon words, created intentionally to describe qualities that no satisfactory words existed for previously? The fact that the new words are not easy to pronounce, and draw symbols from a number of different alphabets seems to suggest the former, unless the anomaly actually affects the ability of languages to describe it (like, by making simpler neologisms seem wrong or inadequate as descriptors), rather than just being innately difficult to describe. Or, I guess a third option, this being specifically DoMc, is the difficulty of pronouncing the words part of the containment? Like, would substituting simpler neologisms allow the anomaly to harm those attempting to describe it, or somehow breach containment through the use of language, as a sort of infectious concept? I dunno, I feel like there's a very interesting idea in here but I'm just a bit lost trying to parse it.







